is queue an ADT or a data structure? I don't want to do anything with data so that would be bad. What do I use ADT for? Also, in your code are you using Java 6 or 7? Thanks!

Comment: @PedroJesusOrtizSoto Sorry it's not really clear, but the linked article is not explaining how `LinkedList` (which is not a `Stack`) is used as an ADT. Instead it explains how `Stack` can be used as an ADT. Since you want to use `LinkedList` (which is not a `Stack`), what can be used as an ADT for you?

Answer: Stack (and list) are not ADTs because they do not have an abstract data type that can be used to access the data element. They are just classes that implement the interface. One can implement an ADT over a given type as follows:

\begin{code}
public abstract class MyAbstractStack
{
 public abstract void Push(Object v);
 public abstract Object Pop();
 public abstract int Size();
}

public class MyStack implements MyAbstractStack
{
 public void Push(Object v) {..}
 public Object Pop() {..}
 public int Size() {...}
}
\end{code}

Answer: A data structure is an abstract data type (ADT) that represents a specific piece of data or collection of data. It is a collection of variables, expressions, and declarations that use generic programming techniques to represent some abstract type of entity.

A stack is a data structure that is typically used to maintain the order of items by removing the top item when you want to add something to it.

Now we can say that a Linked List is not an abstract data type but a struct. Linked lists are implemented in Java through a class, but they are not ADTs. We can implement Linked List as a List that uses linked items, such as Java’s `LinkedList` class.

An abstract data structure can only be referred to as an ADT (Abstract Data Type) when it represents an entity which can be used to perform operations on other entities as a group, it can be an ADT if it can be used to group entities into a single container.

