what is the recommended pattern for creating games in godot? (like separater different scenes, using the scene system, etc.) Does anyone know?

Answer: You can create multiple levels in Godot. Each level is a separate scene with their own script, assets etc.

It is up to you to implement a pattern to switch between scenes (you can use the `Scene_Transition` or use callbacks). Here are some examples:

\section{Callbacks:}

You can pass data to the scenes you want to call with callbacks, and when you want to call a scene you can call its `set_pass_data` method which takes a `Data` object (you can create one on init time). You can then get the data from the scene you want to call by calling `get_pass_data`. Then you can switch between scenes by passing the `call` method or `activate` method depending on your needs.

\section{Scene_Transition:}

The `Scene_Transition` is a built-in helper to switch scenes. It supports different types of transitions like `Instant_Transition`, `Alpha_Transition`, `Alpha_In_Out_Transition` etc. You can use them by creating an instance and configure its properties to set the transition type.

\begin{code}
transition = Scene_Transition() # Create a transition
transition.type = Transition.Type.ALPHA_IN

if event_name:
    transition.call(scene) # Call a scene with a specific event name
else:
    transition.activate(scene) # Just activate any scene
\end{code}

\section{More Examples:}

You can find some more examples in the \em{[Scene system documentation](https://godotengine.org/docs/4.1/classes/class_scene_system.html)} and \em{[Transition system documentation](https://godotengine.org/docs/4.1/classes/class_transition.html)}.

\section{References:}
\begin{itemize}
\item [Scene system documentation](https://godotengine.org/docs/4.1/classes/class_scene_system.html)
\item [Transition system documentation](https://godotengine.org/docs/4.1/classes/class_transition.html)
\item [Godot 4.1 guide to game development](https://learn.godotengine.org/intro/4-1-guide-to-game-development/)
\end{itemize}

