Answer: Duck typing is a philosophy that says that you are free to substitute any type for another in a specific scenario. Typically this has a context of the object/parameter/etc that needs to be replaced where the duck typing is applied. For example:

\begin{code}
let a = "hello world".toUpperCase();

const s = "test";

a = s;

console.log(s);
\end{code}

The `toUpperCase()` function in that example is a duck type. It takes a parameter (a string) and returns a string (uppercased). So you could replace it by any appropriate function, be it converting the string `s` to lowercase or whatever else.

Now, in TypeScript the type system is strict and you can not just ignore the explicit types you declare. However, you have the ability to specify the interface of a type.

For example:

\begin{code}
interface A {
    toUpperCase(): string;
}

const s = "test";

let a = "hello world".toUpperCase();

a = s;

console.log(s);
\end{code}

This is a TypeScript interface declaration. Within a TypeScript module it is possible to import the `A` interface and then declare an object that conforms to it. This interface has a generic parameter declaration (the string `s` in my example). But it does not specify the implementation type.

So, TypeScript could be useful in a context like this:

\begin{code}
interface A {
    toUpperCase(): string;
}

const s = "test";

const a: A = "hello world".toUpperCase(); // Typecasting allowed and possible

a = s; // Compile-time error, the types do not match

console.log(s);
\end{code}

So TypeScript allows you to use interfaces and generic type parameter declarations, but it still enforces the type system and the types you declare. It is not really duck typing, since the types are still specified explicitly.

