I have two remote Debian servers, A and B. How can I copy a directory of files at `~/Documents/training_results` existing on server A to the path `~/training_results` on server B? I have SSH access on my local laptop to each of the servers, but neither of the servers have SSH access to the other.

My intention is to write a script that will copy all files from `~/Documents/training_results` on server A, where the permissions are `drwxr-xr-x 81 root root  3144 Jul 12 12:16 training_results` to the path `~/training_results` on server B, where the permissions are `drwxrwxr-x 111 root root 10240 Jul 10 10:22 training_results` so that I don't have to deal with `chmod` or `sudo` on the local server.

Answer: You can easily do this with `scp` from a script. Here's an example:

\begin{code}
#!/bin/bash
scp $1 ~/training_results
\end{code}

You would need to `cd` into the folder containing `~/Documents/training_results` (in your case `A` in my example) and then run the script.

Here's a link to `man` page on `scp`:
http://linux.die.net/man/1/scp

Answer: \begin{code}
scp -r ./Documents/training_results serverb:~/training_results
\end{code}

scp \em{-r} will recursively copy all subdirectories. This command assumes that you are logged in to serverb:~/ and have permissions to access ~/.

The double dot is used to identify the path on the remote system. If you change /Documents to a different path, replace it as such.

Answer: As an additional suggestion (for those, like me, who would like to copy directories recursively)

\begin{code}
#!/bin/bash

scp -r -C $1 serverb:/training_results
\end{code}

The `-r` option instructs `scp` to recursively copy all directories in the source directory. Setting the `-C` option to the destination directory path makes copying the source directory to one location easier. You could simply copy the code above, changing the destination path to serverb:~/ to your needs.

It's true that in order to do so you should have permission to traverse the directory structure on the remote machine and be able to login as \strong{root}. If you don't have these rights you will need to use `sudo` as a prefix to your commands or use non-privileged user accounts for your remote commands.

Answer: You can simply do it in one simple command if the remote path, `remote1:/training_results` and the local path `~/Documents/training_results` are in the same server.

If you want to copy all the files in the directory you only need to do

\begin{code}
scp -r -t 'remote1:/training_results' "~/Documents/training_results"
\end{code}

That will copy all the files including the subdirectories to the path `~/Documents/training_results` on the local server. `scp -t` stands for `create` so it will create the necessary directories on your local server. `~Documents/training_results` is assumed to exist but you can modify it to point to the directory that you want to copy.

Answer: you could try this one:

\begin{code}
rsync -r -C $1 serverb:/training_results
\end{code}

