In TypeScript, how can I tell the type system "I know that in theory this value may have these multiple types, but in practice I know it will only have this one"

\begin{code}
interface SomeType {
  A: string;
  B: string;
  C: string;
}
interface SomeType2 {
  A: number;
  B: number;
  C: number;
}

const value: SomeType | SomeType2 = {
  A: "A",
  B: "B",
  C: "C",
}

const unknown = value.C; // Invalid or inaccessible
\end{code}

I want unknown to be able to be any of the strings from A, B, or C, but I want the actual value to be "A" because in practice, I know that this value will only be "A" for the time being (i.e. A is validated, but none of the other two is). However, in theory, it could be any one of the three, and so I want TypeScript to be able to infer the type from the actual value that is available, instead of the fact that it could potentially be one of those types. How can one do this?

Answer: If the possible types are known in advance, \strong{intersection} can be used. You can create an interface that contains properties from the union of `SomeType` and `SomeType2` interfaces, like so:

\begin{code}
interface SomeTypeAlias {
  A: string;
  B: string;
}

interface SomeType {
  A: string;
  B: string;
}

interface SomeType2 {
  A: number;
  B: number;
}

type SomeTypeUnion = SomeType | SomeType2;

interface SomeTypeAliasUnion extends SomeTypeAlias, SomeTypeUnion {
  C: string;
}

// this is the type of `value` in your example
const value: SomeTypeAliasUnion = {
  A: "A",
  B: "B",
  C: "C"
};

// in practice, unknown could be any of `SomeType` | `SomeType2`
const unknown: SomeTypeUnion = value.C;
\end{code}

Note that `unknown` could also be `undefined` or `null`, but that's not the point here.

Another option, especially when it's not known in advance, is to use dynamic types. They allow you to do conditional type checking based on runtime conditions:

\begin{code}
interface A {
  a: string;
}

interface B {
  b: string;
}

type Union = A | B;

type DynamicType<T extends Union> = T extends A ? A : T extends B ? B : never;

// use dynamic types to handle unknowns, e.g. `Unknown` in my case
const value: DynamicType<SomeTypeUnion> = {};

// this can now handle unknown property values
const unknown: String = value.a;
\end{code}

I'd also like to mention that it's not good practice to assume that something will always be one or the other, especially if you need to handle them both. In a situation like this, I'd suggest using a union and creating a dedicated type for both `SomeType` and `SomeType2`, or using intersections, as recommended by @Ivanov Alik.

Comment: Thanks for the suggestion! The point here is that in my case I have three different types that could potentially be used, but I only want to use one of them at the time. So I do not want to use dynamic types or intersections. The thing is, with static types I can't tell the type system "I know `unknown` has `A` or `B` or `C`, but I guess TypeScript will choose `C` because `Unknown` is a valid type". How can I change this behavior? Maybe there is another way to do that that I am not aware of.

