Answer: Your question says:

\begin{blockquote}
I tried it myself even with unique keys but still gets a duplicate
record in it.
\end{blockquote}

That implies that you have not tried:

\begin{code}
INSERT INTO table_name (key1, key2) VALUES ("value1", "value2");
\end{code}

Without this code, it is not clear how you are trying to insert duplicates. Your question does not specify, thus the comments.

My suspicions and guess-work:
\begin{itemize}
\item The unique keys are not indexed.
\item You have tried to insert two records for the same "key1" value.
\end{itemize}

The solution is to specify unique indexes on your database.

\begin{code}
CREATE UNIQUE INDEX unq_key1 ON table_name (key1);

INSERT INTO table_name (key1, key2) VALUES ("value1", "value2"); -- OK, unique key
INSERT INTO table_name (key1, key2) VALUES ("value1", "value2"); -- FAIL, duplicate
\end{code}

Additionally, you need to ensure that your application handles the unique key rules:

\begin{code}
if ( !MySqlUtils.insertUnique(db_connection) {
    // handle duplicate
}
\end{code}

A more secure approach would be to reject the duplicate in the database:

\begin{code}
BEGIN TRANSACTION;

INSERT INTO table_name (key1, key2) VALUES ("value1", "value2");

SELECT @@error_variable;     -- true or false, depending on success.

SELECT @@error_message;    -- text from error report

COMMIT;

IF @@error_variable = 1051 THEN -- duplicate
\end{code}

