How do I compare strings in Java?
I've been using the == operator in my program to compare all my strings so far. However, I ran into a bug, changed one of them into .equals() instead, and it fixed the bug.
Is == bad? When should it and should it not be used? What's the difference? Or are equals() only needed in some specific situations? How should I use it when I encounter a string with spaces, or when I encounter one that may come back with new characters when its retrieved?

Answer: It depends on your specific requirements.

With `String`, the difference between `==` and `.equals()` is that the latter returns `true` if the two strings are considered equal regardless of the character order. This allows comparing strings that have been modified through inserting, deleting, or rearranging characters. `==` does not make this distinction.

If you only care for the characters' position, as that is the only part of your strings you are really interested in, `==` should work perfectly fine.

But if you're willing to use `equals()` and be more specific about what part of the string to compare, it will be better as you will be comparing strings specifically, ignoring the character order.

\begin{code}
"String1".equals("String1")
\end{code}

will return `true` without considering the character order.

`String` class also has an overloaded `.equals(Object)` method to compare two `Strings` (which are usually not equal to objects of other classes) that takes a `String` as an argument. This method will still only consider the string representation of an object and, in case two strings are the same object, compare their identity, without considering character order.

If you're willing to work with `char[]` arrays to maintain the order, `Arrays.equals(char[] a, char[] b)` will do the matching of the character arrays.

Again, the use of these methods will depend on what you are trying to do with string manipulation. If you're going to perform string manipulation to sort them, you're going to need `Arrays.equals` to compare `char[]` arrays. But on the other hand, if you're interested in finding differences, `String#equals` should yield the results you want.

Answer: Using `==` can cause issues in Java when you need to compare strings for equality, particularly ones that contain whitespace characters.  Consider the following two examples in which strings are the same except their whitespace characters have been modified:

\begin{code}
String s = "" +
     "  " +
     "   " +
     "    " +
     "     ";
s = s.replaceAll("[\\p{Cs}]+", "");

if(s.equals(""))
System.out.println("Equal");
else
System.out.println("Not equal");
\end{code}

When this code is run, the output will be "Not equal".  This is because all the whitespace characters were removed in the process of replacing all the `\\p{Cs}`, a Unicode whitespace character class.  This means that any whitespace between `  "  "  "  "` are now considered part of the same string, `  "  "  "` is equivalent to `"  "  "` regardless of the ordering (e.g. whether it is single quotes or double quotes), but for `s.equals` it doesn't know this and will only look at identical character representations (as `String#equals` would).

So, you need to use the `equals` method to compare strings that contain whitespace and to get correct results:

\begin{code}
if(s.equals("  "  "  "  "))
 System.out.println("Equal");
else
 System.out.println("Not equal");
\end{code}

Note that `String#equals` doesn't give any information about whether the two strings have identical characters - the two strings are only equal if they are identical, regardless of any character order.

On the other hand, you can use `matches` instead of `equals`.  This method matches the entire strings, including whitespace characters, which mean it won't consider the whitespace characters to be separate characters when comparing, and will also ignore `String#equals` rules.  However, it won't take into account string lengths or character case when comparing two strings:

\begin{code}
if("  "  "  "  " matches("  "  "  "  "))
 System.out.println("Equal");

