Answer: One way to solve this is to use a `Recursive` algorithm where the function `solve` will keep calling itself until it gets to the answer `10`, `109` or `1009` .

I recommend using a recursive approach rather than `Iterative` because you can only calculate the `O` notation for `Recursive` algorithms(which is good) but iterative methods cannot do this(which is not good). An Iterative method will only calculate how many time `f()` will take (which is irrelevant in this case) to compute the solution. The `O` notation tells us how many instructions the algorithm needs (which is good) and on a large problem set it will take less time than iterative methods(which is good).

Here's the pseudo-code of the `Recursive Algorithm`:

\begin{code}
function solve(num) {
    if (num == 10 || num == 109 || num == 1009) {
        return num;
    } else {
        // return sol(solve(num / 10)) + num % 10;
        solve(num / 10)
        + num % 10
    }
}
\end{code}

To explain, the first `if` statement will handle the cases where `num == 10, 109, or 1009`, so it returns the correct answer, but for any other case the function `solve` calls itself recursively using `solve(num / 10)` and adds `num % 10` at the end.

The downside of using `Recursive` method is that it will take more time to compute because it keeps calling the self over itself until it gets to the correct answer. That being said, using a smaller `num` will speed up the algorithm, for example we can use `solve(100000)` instead of `solve(1000000)`, but the problem arises when we need to solve a large problem set.

To conclude, recursive solutions are good to solve dynamic programming problems, especially in interviews, and the `O`-notation is the main concern when it comes to performance. Note that you should use smaller `num` to improve the performance.

