Create a short, concise summary of the paper based on its abstract.

Few-shot learning (FSL) is one of the key future steps in machine learning and raises a lot of attention. In this paper, we focus on the FSL problem of dialogue understanding, which contains two closely related tasks: intent detection and slot filling. Dialogue understanding has been proven to benefit a lot from jointly learning the two sub-tasks. However, such joint learning becomes challenging in the few-shot scenarios: on the one hand, the sparsity of samples greatly magnifies the difficulty of modeling the connection between the two tasks; on the other hand, how to jointly learn multiple tasks in the few-shot setting is still less investigated. In response to this, we introduce FewJoint, the first FSL benchmark for joint dialogue understanding. FewJoint provides a new corpus with 59 different dialogue domains from real industrial API and a code platform to ease FSL experiment set-up, which are expected to advance the research of this field. Further, we find that insufficient performance of the few-shot setting often leads to noisy sharing between two sub-task and disturbs joint learning. To tackle this, we guide slot with explicit intent information and propose a novel trust gating mechanism that blocks low-confidence intent information to ensure high quality sharing. Besides, we introduce a Reptile-based meta-learning strategy to achieve better generalization in unseen few-shot domains. In the experiments, the proposed method brings significant improvements on two datasets and achieve new state-of-the-art performance.

The paper is organized as follows:\vspace{-10pt}

\begin{itemize}
\setlength\itemsep{1pt}
\item In section \ref{sec:relatedwork}, we review the related work on few-shot learning in dialogue understanding and the state-of-the-art methods in the field.\vspace{-10pt}
\item In section \ref{sec:dataset}, we describe the process of collecting and annotating the FewJoint dataset , as well as introduce the few-shot dialogue system framework.
\item In section \ref{sec:method}, we elaborate on the key components of our joint learning model, including the slot-guided intent decoding, trust gating module, and the meta-learning strategy.
\item In section \ref{sec:experiment}, we provide performance evaluations of our method, and compare competitive results with the state-of-the practice methods on the FewJoint dataset.
\item In section \ref{sec:conclusion}, we conclude with a summary of our main contributions, limitations and future directions of work.\vspace{-10pt}

\end{itemize}

\section{Related Work}\label{sec:relatedwork}

To tackle the difficult few-shot learning scenarios, a handful of related works have been developed recently, including meta-learning, pre-training, and knowledge distillation. In this section, we review the related works on few-shot learning, the state-of-the-art methods in the field and discuss the main insights gained.

\subsection{Few-Shot Learning}

Traditionally, few-shot learning refers to the ability of a system to learn a new task from a few exemplar training samples. Generally, the few-shot setting aims to provide a system with a limited number of labeled examples to learn from. This type of learning is widely recognized to be a significant challenge. Meta-learning is proposed as a flexible way to tackle the learning of few-shot problems. Meta-learning employs meta-optimization algorithms to solve the few-shot learning problem.

Previous works often use a meta-learning task distribution \cite{wang2016learning,triantafillou2019meta,yang2019meta}, which provides a strategy to solve the task from a limited number of training samples. Meta-optimization algorithms usually use different strategies for learning and sharing \cite{li2019episodic,finn2017maml} and meta-learning can be divided into four major categories: Episodic, Online, Offline, and Mix-type \cite{li2019episodic,wang2016learning,triantafillou2019meta}. For instance, Online Learning \cite{finn2017maml} uses an off-policy approach to meta-train an estimator on a large number of tasks and, at test time, an online model is updated to the task. This method focuses on making the model general

