Answer: \strong{Problem}

The problem is that you are trying to convert `print` to a ruby string.

\strong{Ruby syntax}

If you want to get the ruby command to output, you need to escape the " characters in the `print` command.

\begin{code}
print("Hello world!")
\end{code}

becomes:

\begin{code}
print("Hello world!")
\end{code}

\strong{Solution}

To convert any `print` commands, you need to extract the arguments to `print` to escape only the arguments to `print`, not the `print` command itself:

\begin{code}
command = "print(42)"
new_command = command.split("(")[0]
new_command = new_command.gsub("print", "print ")
new_command = new_command.strip()
\end{code}

The above code will return:

\begin{code}
"print(42)"
\end{code}

Now you can pass it back to ruby to output:

\begin{code}
output = convert_command_to_ruby(new_command)

print output
#=> "print(42)"

# If you want to pass back as it is (i.e. without parsing it)
# without needing to escape the " characters
# output = convert_command_to_ruby("print(42)")
# => "print(42)"
\end{code}

